cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Hi Everyone and welcome to today's Precision Club session, in which we start the second portion of this course and start looking at Super-Precision Asking Bids.

This part of the series will take a couple of months in all.

Generally speaking the Asking Bids are not going to be much, if any, use to you unless you are going to play Precision as it is not very easy or practical to graft them onto systems like 2/1 or Standard American.

This is certainly not a "basic" topic.

If you're not familiar with "Basic Precision" Openings and Responses, then this will be a very difficult session for you to follow or to get anything from.

You're welcome to stay anyway and hopefully you'll find this interesting but I also guarantee that you will find it confusing if you've not attended most of the sessions in this Series thus far.

I apologise to anyone who is put out by this, but there's not much point in confusing yourself by introducing an advanced topic into your system if you're not au fait with the basics.

If you're in that position please stay by all means, but have the paracetamol ready to hand, LOL!|
pg| ***** 2 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  If you have not already done so, please have a look at the notes I have prepared on Precision Club bidding.

You can find these on:  ^*h http://ocp.pigpen.org.uk/AskingBids.php ^*n You will DEFINITELY want to have these onscreen in the background for reference during this session.

If you are new to Asking Bids then there's no way you're going to absorb everything we cover tonight, so please do visit the site and read through the Asking Bid section at your leisure.

If you want, download one of the Precision system documents on the site, they cover this stuff in more detail.

Visit  ^*h http://ocp.pigpen.org.uk/Documents.php ^*n


^^|fp|t-title|at|Principles and Underlying Rules|fp||at|^^^^|

at|Okay, there's a great deal of introductory stuff on Asking Bids before we get to the Asking Bids themselves, so please bear with me.

Mostly, today, we're going to be concerned with GENERAL PRINCIPLES and UNDERLYING RULES for Asking Bids.

We will start on the Asking Bids themselves next week.

Super-Precision Asking Bids really are the fun side of Precision but they are a LOT of hard work to start with.

Asking Bid sequences normally occur after a POSITIVE response to a  1@C  Opening but can commence with a jump-shift over an intermediate Precision Opening  (eg: 1@D - 2@S),  and elsewhere.

The system I teach makes extensive use of Asking Bids and they are, in my view, what makes the system soar majestically above other varieties of Precision and certainly above other systems.|
pg| ***** 3 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Asking Bids are unequivocably SLAM INVESTIGATIONS.

That doesn't mean that you are committed to play in a slam, but we are ALWAYS in a game-forcing situation if Asking Bids are used.

They are normally used BY the strong hand (asking the questions) with the weaker hand answering the questions (but not always).

The Asker is therefore not revealing anything much about their hand but, by the end of the Asking Bid sequence knows all (hopefully) the salient points about the responding hand.

In many instances you will find that the "Asker" can virtually write down partner's hand at the end of the sequence.

We also aim that the stronger hand will normally become Declarer, but this is not always possible.

Firstly there is no longer any such thing as a "standard" set of Asking Bids.

What I'm going to introduce to you over the next few weeks might have started life as "standard" Super-precision Asking Bids 40 years ago, but over the years they've been refined and tuned, and they're based on the set of Asking Bids that I developed with Jason Hackett in the 1980's, but which have now been developed further still.

I originally used Eric Jannerstern's excellent book on Precision Club, but the Asking Bids now bear very little relation to what you'll find in there, or indeed to what you'll find in Garozzo & Belladonna's definitive book on Super-Precision.

The moral is that you really must get yourself a regular Precision partner if you're going to bother with Asking Bids.

Learn and practice the Asking Bids together.

Don't expect to sit down opposite an unknown Precision player and have any kind of instinctive meeting of minds where Asks are concerned, because it's very unlikely to happen unless you're confining yourself to Asking Bids like Alpha, Beta, Gamma and Epsilon.|
pg| ***** 4 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Asking Bids require a LOT of partnership discussion and hard grafting practice to get the hang of them.

This takes time and a LOT of effort, but the results speak for themselves.

Jason and I discussed and practised these Asking Bids for several MONTHS before we actually used them in anger.

I really can recommend you get into the Partnership Bidding Rooms for this purpose.

You can set the conditions there so you are always getting dealt game or slam hands and get some CONCENTRATED practice on these sequences.

I use the letters of the Greek alphabet to name the Asking Bids I use.

There are other "schemes" such as TAB (Trump Asking Bid), CAB(Control Asking Bid) etc, but I find that that's too generic and doesn't help when you have about 6 different Trump Asking Bids and, in any case, they give give me a pain in the abs.

So I use Alpha, Beta, Gamma etc.


Any questions or comments thus far?


The valium working nicely, I see :)|
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Ok, let's firstly deal with some of the more general concepts behind Asking Bids: The responses to Precision Asking Bids are in STEPS above the Asking Bid itself, so we tend to talk about a 2-step response, 3-step response etc.

Thus if  2@S  is the Ask, then  
^c@2
2NT  ^dis the 1-step response,  
3@C  ^dis the 2-step response and  
3@D  ^dis the 3-step response, etc etc etc.
^b@2
The Ask normally relates to the suit bid, but the response never does, except by coincidence.

It goes without saying that Asking Bids AND Responses need to be alerted fully :)

As we'll see a bit later on when we consider Interference over Asking Bid sequences, there are some occasions (when Opps interfere over the ASK) when Double/Redouble becomes the 1-step response, Pass becomes the 2-step response, and the first actual "step" is the 3-step response, in an attempt to recover lost space.


Asking Bids are asking VERY SPECIFIC questions about partner's hand.

eg:  "What is your EXACT holding is in Hearts"  or  "What degree of control do you have in Clubs?"  or  "How many Aces and Kings have you got?".

Each Asking Bid has a range of possible responses, some open-ended and others with a limit on the number of steps responder can bid.

All the stepped responses have tightly pre-defined meanings.|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


bt||
nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Furthermore, the range of steps and their meaning for a given Asking Bid often changes according to the exact circumstances.

If, for example, Responder has already shown 4+ Controls in response to an earlier Ask, there's no point having a scale for Controls that starts 0-2, 3, 4, 5, so in that situation we'd use a scale that starts 0-4, 5, 6, 7.

Any questions on the idea of stepped responses?


^^|fp|t-title|at|Terminology|fp||at|^^^^|

at|Alright, let's cover some terminology first: When we start talking about CONTROLS generally, we're dealing with Aces and Kings.

In "Precision-speak" an Ace is worth 2 Controls, and a King worth 1 Control.

Thus a hand like    @SAQJxx  @HKJ7x  @DQx  @CAK    contains 6 controls.

The Alpha, Beta and Zeta  Asking Bids enquire about the number of Controls partner has in their hand.


Let's look at a full deal.|
