|fp|t-title|at|Repeat Asks|fp||at|^^^^|

at|A quick look at Repeat Asks.

Most of the Asking Bids have the facility of a REPEAT Ask, if necessary.

These questions are clarifying Responder's holding in some way and the answers are ALWAYS dependent on the answer to the INITIAL question.|
pg| ***** 15 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Thus if the strong hand makes an Epsilon Ask (about the degree of control held in a side suit) in Clubs, and gets a response of "2nd and 3rd round control", a subsequent ask in the SAME suit (which doesn't have to be immediate) would be asking what KIND of "2nd & 3rd" round control responder has [Kx, KQx, KQ stiff, KQxx(x), KQJx(x)], ALL of which holdings are 2nd and 3rd round control.

Where Responder has shown 2 degrees of control in response to the first Ask (eg: 1st & 3rd, 2nd & 3rd, 1st & 2nd), a second ask in that suit is asking about the nature of the lower degree of control.

Thus is the first ask got an answer stating "2nd & 3rd round control", a repeat ask is asking what KIND of 3rd round control Responder has (because the 2nd round control will always be an honour) 

So Kx is 2nd and 3rd round control, because the King provide the second round control, but on the 3rd round they'll be able to ruff.
^^

|fp|t-title|at|Rules|fp||at|

Now we move on to some of the "rules" that underpin our use of Asking Bids.

These you must get to know until they are second nature, because you cannot successfully use Asking Bids unless you know them completely.

Some of the "rules" are specific to particular Asking Bids and we'll cover those when we get to the Asking Bid in question, but...

The critical point is that there can NEVER be any doubt as to WHICH Asking bid is being used at any one time.|
pg| ***** 16 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Some Asks are only used in very specific circumstances, the relative importance of agreeing trumps, finding out partner's general level of controls, and finding out about controls in a specific side-suit all determine which Asking Bid is being used.

This might seem improbable to you now, but as we move through the Asking Bids, you will see how the rules governing this work.

There is NEVER any doubt about which ask is being used.

The "rules" concern the relative "importance" of the various types of Asking Bid: 
^d@2
^c[1]  Agreeing trumps is the most important thing, You can't start asking about control in a side suit if you don't know what the trump suit is (and therefore which suits ARE the side suits).

Thus Trump Asking Bids generally take precedence and Epsilon (asking about controls in a side suit) cannot be used UNLESS we've already specifically "agreed" a trump suit.

^c[2]  Similarly, there normally not much point in floundering about Asking about degrees of control in side suits (with Epsilon) if you've no idea how many controls partner has in total, so finding out about partner's GENERAL level of controls is the number two priority.

^c[3]  Finding out about the specific degree of control partner has in side suits is generally the least important thing and so is the lowest thing on the Asking Bid totem pole.
^b@2
So (1) Agreeing trumps, (2) General Controls, and (3) Specific Controls is the order that determines things.

This is not a straight jacket, though, but it is the touchstone that decides which Asking bid is being used if there is any potential doubt.

(This will become clearer as we proceed).|
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Trump Asking Bids always take precedence to start with, but once we've agreed a trump suit, ALL of those Asks (apart from repeat asks) are put away, "back on the shelf" and only Control asks are available.

Clearly there will be some hands where the ONLY thing you need to find out is, for example, partner's SPECIFIC degree of control in one particular suit.

The rest of their hand might be totally irrelevant.

The rules for Asking Bids merely set an order of priority for the Asking Bids.They do not mandate that you ALWAYS have to use the Asking Bids in the same sequence.

It merely determines WHICH Asking Bids are available and where.

Thus if we've agreed Spades as trumps, for example, and the last "response" was  3NT,  then  4@C  Beta (General Controls) TAKES PRECEDENCE over  4@C  Epsilon (SPECIFIC Control in Clubs), because General Controls has a higher priority than suit-specific control.

It doesn't mean you HAVE to bid  4@C  over the  3NT  response.

The Asker always decides what information they require most urgently and what they can and cannot afford to ask about.

On the other hand, if we'd already established Responder's exact level of control earlier in the auction, then  4@C  WOULD be Epsilon, because Beta is out of the window.

Similarly I have to stress that you CANNOT make an Epsilon Ask UNLESS we've actually agreed trumps first.|
pg| ***** 18 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  So if you in the position that you have a monster hand with a long solid Heart suit and are only interested in finding out whether or not partner has the Queen of Spades, you must get Hearts agreed FIRST (by whatever means) before you can enquire about partner's Spade holding.

You "knowing" that Hearts is where you want to play the hand doesn't count, because partner doesn't know your Heart holding.

This is quite a common area of confusion for those new to Asking Bids.

You have to use the MECHANISM of Asking Bids to agree the suit even if it's blindingly obvious to you (the asker) that that is going to be the trump suit.

Any questions of the relative order or priority of the different KINDS of Asking Bids?

I think at this stage, this is enough talk from me.

