fp|t-title|at|Positive and Negative Trump Responses|fp||at|^^^^|

cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  That brings us nicely onto the next topic:

Another concept to grasp is that most of the Trump Asking bids to do with assessing trumps have negative responses and positive responses.

These are positive and negative in terms of whether the suit is subsequently agreed as trumps for the rest of the sequence.

If the Ask gets a POSITIVE response, then the suit is agreed as trumps and all OTHER Trump Asking Bids go into the bucket.

If the Ask gets a NEGATIVE response, then we've NOT agreed a suit and Trump Asking Bids are still active.

So if the response to the Trump Ask is "negative", then the suit is not automatically agreed as trumps, and normally the Asker can ask again in the same suit or in a different suit.

Some Asks automatically agree the suit as trumps by the mere fact that they are used (eg: Gamma & Eta, both of which are asking about RESPONDER's suit) and another unconditionally SETS a suit as trumps, whatever Responder's holding (ie: Zeta).

The rules for trump agreement are different for each kind of trump asking bid.

When the strong hand is asking about one of THEIR OWN suits, and since we're usually asking about 5+-card suits, a response that shows at least  Hxx  or  xxxx  always agrees the suit as trumps (and a holding of "HH" often does too).

We'll come back to the criteria for trump agreement in more detail when we cover each of the Trump Asking Bids.|
pg| ***** 69 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
fp|t-title|at|Bidding Space|fp||at|^^^^|

cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Bidding Space is almost always at a premium in Asking Bid sequences.

For this reason, as I mentioned earlier, some of the Asking Bids have different "Ranges" available to try to make optimum use of the space available whilst still maintaining the required degree of "precision" in the response.

Beta, for example, is our equivalent of Blackwood and asks how many Aces and Kings partners hand has.

There are actually SIX different ranges for Beta (Normal, Weak, Special-Weak, Strong, Super and Range).

To give you some idea the Normal range for Beta is used when partner's exact strength is unknown or when it is known to be intermediate (and the stepped responses are 0-2, 3, 4, 5...).

The Weak Scale is used when partner is known to be weak (0-10) or known to have less than 4 Controls (and the stepped responses are 0, 1, 2, 3, 4).

We saw an example of the weak scale in action in the  Teach 1  deal.  

The Strong scale is used when partner is KNOWN to be 16+ (relatively rare unless Responder is asking the questions over a 2@D Opening) or more commonly when partner is already KNOWN to have 4 or more controls 
 (eg: 2 or 4 step response to a previous Alpha Ask, both of which show 4+ Controls).

Apart from the Special Weak scale (which we'll cover next week), the other Beta ranges are fairly rare and you needn't worry about them overmuch.

Any questions?|
pg| ***** 70 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
fp|t-title|at|Captain's Choices|fp||at|^^^^|

cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Once a suit has been agreed as trumps, Asking Bids tend to continue until the Captain of the Hand returns to the agreed trump suit at game level or above, unless this bid is obviously invitational (eg: a jump to the 5-level in an agreed major suit).

However, a jump-shift into a suit OTHER than the agreed trump suit is almost ALWAYS "to play".

Sometimes for economy the Captain has to "lie" by pretending to agree one suit as trumps, all the while knowing that he is eventually going to play in a different one.

For example, Opener might have a very long solid suit (AKQJ10xx) but not want to impose that suit as trumps unconditionally, because they want to find out Responder's holding.

Using Alpha would probably take THREE asks in the suit, so perhaps agreeing RESPONDER's suit is a cheap alternative and then jump-shifting into their suit later in the bidding.|
pg| ***** 71 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
fp|t-title|at|Which sequence to choose?|fp||at|^^^^|

cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Which sequence to choose ?  Well experience and judgement count for a lot here.

There is almost always more than one possible route and it is often impossible to tell to start with which will end up being the most economical one.

Economy is always worth striving for.

...but it cannot be guaranteed...

The trick is to continually evaluate the information you've gained thus far, and take ALL of the inferences from the responses you've had.

Sometimes the answer to one "question" will mean that you don't have to ask a different question about another suit.

Sometimes you have to change direction because of an unexpected response.

Be flexible.

Asking Bids do take a HUGE amount of concentration and effort to get right.  

We saw an example of that in the first example hand (Teach 1).  

However, the effort taken to learn the Asks and Responses, to learn the underlying rules that govern which ask is being used, and the degree of concentration required to put all this to good effect is REALLY worth the effort as sometimes Asking Bids will guide you to the correct contract when few if any other pairs are able to get there, if relying on "natural" methods.|
